ecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/).</license-p></license></permissions><self-uri xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" content-type="pmc-pdf" xlink:href="main.pdf"/><custom-meta-group><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-qastatus</meta-name><meta-value>0</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-live</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-embargo</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-released</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-open-access</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-olf</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-manuscript</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-legally-suppressed</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-has-pdf</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-has-supplement</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-pdf-only</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-suppress-copyright</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-is-real-version</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-is-scanned-article</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-preprint</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-in-epmc</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-license-ref</meta-name><meta-value>CC BY-NC-ND</meta-value></custom-meta></custom-meta-group></article-meta></front><body><p content-type="salutation">Dear Editor,</p><p id="p0010">We read with interest Javier et al.'s article on SGLT2 inhibitors in hypertensive CKD patients [<xref rid="bib1" ref-type="bibr">1</xref>]. While addressing an important question, several limitations warrant consideration.</p><p id="p0015">First, the hypertension definition (SBP ≥140 mmHg) is outdated, diverging from guidelines recommending ≥130 mmHg for high-risk CKD. This likely excludes stage 1 hypertensive patients (SBP 130–139 mmHg) who face significant cardiorenal risk. Olsen et al. [<xref rid="bib2" ref-type="bibr">2</xref>] showed diabetic patients achieving SBP 130–139 mmHg had 47.6% lower renal deterioration risk (HR 0.524; 95%CI 0.375–0.733) and 55.8% lower ESKD risk (HR 0.442; 95%CI 0.196–1.000) versus SBP ≥140 mmHg, with similar protection in non-diabetics. Future studies should adopt guideline-aligned thresholds.</p><p id="p0020">Second, baseline antihypertensive medication interactions were unexplored. While RAS inhibitor and diuretic use are reported, potential synergies/antagonisms with SGLT2 inhibitors remain unexamined. SGLT2 inhibitors complement RAS inhibition but concomitant diuretics may increase hypotension/AKI risk in advanced CKD [<xref rid="bib3" ref-type="bibr">3</xref>]. Subgroup analyses are needed to assess heterogeneity by background therapy.</p><p id="p0025">Third, blood pressure variability (BPV)—a key predictor surpassing mean BP—was overlooked. Yang et al. [<xref rid="bib4" ref-type="bibr">4</xref>] found high BPV associated with 21% increased CKD progression risk. Fletcher et al. [<xref rid="bib5" ref-type="bibr">5</xref>] showed canagliflozin reduced mean but not variability SBP, while each 1-SD variability increase raised heart failure hospitalization by 19%. Russo et al. [<xref rid="bib6" ref-type="bibr">6</xref>] found dapagliflozin reduced arterial stiffness independent of 24-h SBP, suggesting non-pressure pathways. Future studies should incorporate BPV with ambulatory monitoring.</p><p id="p0030">In summary, the outdated threshold, lack of interaction analysis, and omission of BPV limit generalizability. Future research should integrate guideline-aligned thresholds, drug interaction analyses, and ambulatory monitoring to better assess SGLT2 inhibitors' net benefit in hypertensive CKD.</p><sec id="sec1"><title>CRediT authorship contribution statement</title><p id="p0035"><bold>Zhenxing Deng:</bold> Writing – original draft. <bold>Shaoxun Wen:</bold> Conceptualization, Writing – review &amp; editing.</p></sec><sec id="sec2"><title>Funding</title><p id="p0040">None.</p></sec><sec sec-type="COI-statement" id="coi0010"><title>Declaration of competing interest</title><p id="p0045">The authors declare that they have no known competing financial interests or personal relationships that could have influenced the work reported in this paper.</p></sec></body><back><ref-list id="cebib0010"><title>References</title><ref id="bib1"><label>1</label><element-citation publication-type="journal" id="sref1"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name name-style="western"><surname>Javier</surname><given-names>R.M.</given-names></name><name name-style="western"><surname>Faizin</surname><given-names>I.</given-names></name><name name-style="western"><surname>Andiani</surname><given-names>Samudra D.</given-names></name><name name-style="western"><surname>Puspitasari</surname><given-names>R.A.</given-names></name><name name-style="western"><surname>Dharma</surname><given-names>A.S.</given-names></name><etal/></person-group><article-title>Renal and cardiovascular effects of SGLT2 inhibitors among hypertensive patients with chronic kidney disease: a systematic review and meta-analysis</article-title><source>Int. J. Cardiol. Cardiovasc. Risk. Prevent.</source><volume>29</volume><year>2026</year><object-id pub-id-type="publisher-id">200585</object-id><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1016/j.ijcrp.2026.200585</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="pmcid">PMC12907684</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">41704674</pub-id></element-citation></ref><ref id="bib2"><label>2</label><